Pet kiting. This is where a pet class runs around in a circle with their pet on a melee who can't hit back because of the melee range bug. This is extremely lame since the melee has no chance ot hit back.
[/quote]<br>
<br>
Explain to me, how is a mage for example, going to kill a rogue - without the ability to kite you with his pet? you can kill him in close to one backstab, or in a few attack rounds, he cant channel spells through dual wield, and all his spells only does 66percent of their damage against you, not counting your ressists.<br>
<br>
No thats right, he cant.<br>
<br>
[quote] 
Levitate. 2 things. 1) hovering over water and casting on people who can't hit you. 2) floating way the hell in the air where you can't be hit.

Solution- Either improve pumice or make it so you can't cast any offensive spells while levitated like scale of wolf
[/quote]<br>
<br>
yeah its really unfair that one of his spells actually works as intended, he can fly, you cant. tough luck, atleast you arent suffering from a gimped highly ressistable damage output.<br>
<br>
[quote] 
Shaman dmg shield potions. There is absolutely nothing wrong with these being around except for the fact that they stack with druid and mage ds. This brings the druids potential dmg shield from 38 to a ridiculous 69 per hit.

Solution-Make the potions and druid/mage ds the same spell line so they wont stack.
[/quote]<br>
<br>
One of the few things casters can use that actually has a use against melees. as a druid my damage shield is nice, but its just not enough, any halfassed melee can kill me easily even though its up. using a potion he actually have to use a pumice or two before killing me, heavens forbid it. i do agree that it might seem insane, but if you think about it, all it does is to make people think a bit before going into combat. making hitting autoattack against a caster not meaning instant win anymore :P<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
